���������������������Thank you for your letter
concerning the UNIX time-sharing system.
Enclosed is a preprint of an article which
will be published in the
Communications of the ACM in their issue
devoted to papers from last year's
SIGOPS conference.

At the moment,
UNIX is available,
for a nuisance fee of about $100,
to educational institutions.
The more detailed
UNIX reference manual is only available
with such a licence.
In order to get the "official"
word concerning release,
you should contact:

aThank you for your letter concerning the chess
program for the PDP-11.
There are certain problems involved in releasing chess.
The program is writen in a local language which is
considered proprietary.
For speed,
parts of the program are writen in a local
varient of PDP-11 assembly language.
In addition,
the program and associated table compilers
all run under the UNIX time-sharing system,
which is also considered proprietary.
.sp
If after all this,
you believe that listings
in two undocumented languages,
calling on undocumented system I/O routines,
would be of use,
I will try to get them released.
On the other hand,
if you are really interested in running
the program,
you should consider obtaining UNIX,
which is available under a Western Electric
license agreement, royality-free, to educational institutions.
For information on the UNIX agreement,
you should contact:
